{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_016R1AFeaX6CB7RZv4fPzBTp","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Wait - pod-1 is the PRIMARY. I should upgrade the secondaries first before the primary. Let me reconsider.\n\nThe current state:\n- pod-0: SECONDARY, mongo:6.0\n- pod-1: PRIMARY, mongo:6.0\n- pod-2: SECONDARY, mongo:7.0.5\n\nWith partition=1, it will only update pods with index >= 1. Since pod-1 is the primary, I should:\n\nActually wait - with partition=1, that means all pods with ordinal >= partition will be updated. \n\nSo pods 1 and 2 will be considered for update. Pod-2 is already on 7.0.5, but pod-1 will get updated. The issue is that pod-1 is the primary - when it gets deleted and recreated, MongoDB will lose the primary, trigger an election, and pod-1 will rejoin as a secondary. This is risky but workable with partition=1 since it will upgrade the primary anyway. Wait, I need to reconsider the partition logic here. Pod-0 has ordinal 0, so it won't be updated when partition=1. Since StatefulSet rolling updates proceed in reverse ordinal order, setting partition=0 after pod-2 is done would update pod-1 first (the current primary), then pod-0. That's the correct sequence to minimize downtime. So the issue is that in phase 2, pod-1 is now PRIMARY on 6.0, which means updating it during partition=1 would disrupt the primary. I need to step down the current primary first before continuing with the rolling update, or adjust the partition strategy to avoid updating the active primary. So with partition=1 already set, pod-1 (the current primary) will restart with the new image. During that restart, pod-0 and pod-2 will elect a new primary, and pod-1 will rejoin as a secondary on 7.0.5.\n\nAfter that completes, I'll set partition=0 to upgrade pod-0, the last remaining node on the old version.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cac